## Quick Exercise -- Find the Roots

Find the roots of the following polynomials
a) $z^2-1$?
b) $z^2+1$?

The first polynomial has two real roots (one repeated twice). The second polynomial has two imaginary roots.
→ Recall the [fundamental theorem of algebra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_algebra)

## Complex Numbers

> Complex numbers are a powerful way to represent signals

A complex number can be represented in the form $z=x+jy$
- Where $j^2=-1$

![Pasted image 20220517210823.png](data:image/png;base64,)

> [!note]
> Some polynomials have no real roots (e.g. $z^2 + 1$), but all order-N polynomials have N (possibly complex, possible repeated) roots.

> [!hint] An aside on j, the imaginary unit
> $j=\sqrt{-1}$
> $j^2=-1$
> $j^3=-j$
> $j^4=1$
> *Recall that this pattern repeats as power is incremented by 1*

## Operations with Complex Numbers

### Complex Addition = Vector Addition

- Complex addition can be performed the same way as vector addition
- Add the real and imaginary components separately

**Exercise**: Add $z_1 = 4 – 3j$ to $z_2 = 2 + 5j$

> [!check] Solution
> ![Pasted image 20220517212326.png|300](data:image/png;base64,)
> $$z_3=z_1+z_2=(4-j3)+(2+j5)=(4+2)+j(-3+5)=6+j2$$


### Complex Multiply = Vector Rotation

- Multiplication/division ==scales and rotates== vectors
- When dividing, magnitude is divided and phase is subtracted

![Pasted image 20220517220408.png|400](data:image/png;base64,)

### Powers

- Involves repeated multiplication
- Rotating by equal angle size

![Pasted image 20220517220545.png](data:image/png;base64,)

> [!tldr] Bottom line
> **Cartesian**: add, subtract
> **Polar**: multiply, divide, power

## Euler’s Formula and Euler’s Identity

Consider: What is the most beautiful equation?
- Google search yields the answer $e^{j\pi}+1=0$
- This equation is called Euler’s Identity
- Operations with two irrational numbers, resulting in 0

## Complex conjugate (z*)

> [!important] Definition: Complex Conjugate
> To obtain the complex conjugate $z^*$ of a vector $z$, change the sign of **all** $j$‘s
> - In other words, we change the sign of the imaginary component
>
> **Rectangular form**
> $z=x+jy$
> $z^*=x-jy$
>
> **Polar form**
> $z=re^{j\theta}$
> $z^*=re^{-j\theta}$

![Pasted image 20220517214012.png|300](data:image/png;base64,)
- Complex conjugation reflects the vector about the real axis

> [!tip] Aside on cos() and sin()
> $$\cos(\theta)=cos(-\theta)$$
> $$\sin(\theta)=-sin(-\theta)$$
> Note how cosine is an even function. We can observe that the real component (obtained through cosine) is not affected when we find the complex conjugate.

### Uses of Conjugation

- When dividing two complex numbers in rectangular form, we may make the denominator real
	- Multiply both the numerator and denominator by the complex conjugate of the denominator
	- Recall: $(a+b)(a-b)=a^2-b^2$
	- $zz^*=(a+bj)(a-bj)=a^2-b^2j^2=a^2+b^2=r^2$

### Using Conjugates: Inverse Euler⭐⭐⭐

![Pasted image 20220517215829.png|500](data:image/png;base64,)
*We can see the connection between sinusoids and complex numbers.*

> [!important]
> In other words…
> - $z+z^*$ yields $2\Re\{z\}$
> - $z-z^*$ yields $2j\Im\{z\}$

## Roots of Unity – Example Problem

Find values of $z$ for which:
$$(z-5)^{10}+1024=0$$

**Hint**: Let $x=z-5$. We now have the equation $x^{10}+1024=0$ to solve.

## Roots of Unity – General Form of Solution

==important== ⭐⭐⭐

$$z ^ N=C$$
- $z=re^{j\theta}$
	- Therefore, $z^N=r^Ne^{jN\theta}$
- $C=|C|e^{j\phi}e^{j2\pi k}=|C|e^{j(\phi+2\pi k)}$
	- $X =|C|e^{j\phi}$ and $e^{j2\pi k} = 1$

**We now have the equation**
$$z^N=r^Ne^{jN\theta}=|C|e^{j(\phi+2\pi k)}$$
- $r^N=|C| \rightarrow r=|C|^{1/N}$
- $N\theta=\phi+2\pi k \rightarrow \theta= \frac{\phi}{N}+ \frac{2\pi k}{N}$

==Hooray we have both magnitude and phase==

> [!example]
> Solve for $z$, given $z^6=j$
>
> **Answer**: r = 1, $\theta = \frac{\pi}{12}+ \frac{2\pi k}{6}$
> - Note how $\theta$ contains an initial angle/changes when k = 0. This as a result rotates all solutions.
